#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""sable-msg — inter-agent messaging over tmux send-keys (SABLE-bldh.1).

Scoped to the LEAD<->MANAGER conversation (Lincoln <-> Optimus/Tarzan), plus
bead-addressed delivery to a specific WORKER pane (SABLE-6izz, via --bead).
Workers are otherwise never messaged directly — they are spawned per-bead with
their instructions and report via the bead pool. The message IS the turn: we
type a single line into the recipient's claude prompt and submit it. No inbox,
no injection hook.

The recipient pane is found via the role->pane registry, which is just tmux's
own per-pane user-option `@sable_role` (self-cleaning: dead panes vanish from
tmux). `sable-tmux` and `sable-spawn-worker` set `@sable_role` when they create
panes. Workers all share the generic `@sable_role=worker`, so a specific
worker is instead addressed by its `@sable_bead` tag via --bead (SABLE-6izz):
`sable-msg <bead-id> "..." --bead`. That lookup is restricted to panes already
tagged @sable_role=worker — the default role-only lookup used for manager
names never consults @sable_bead, so a manager send can never accidentally
land on a worker pane even if some tag is stale.

Delivery is VERIFIED, not assumed (SABLE-bq93): tmux send-keys exiting 0 only
proves the keystrokes were injected, not that the recipient's TUI actually
accepted them as a submitted turn — a booting pane or an Escape hitting a
blocking gate can silently swallow them (the same boot / dropped-Enter race
documented as SABLE-91m3 and guarded against in sable-spawn-worker). We reuse
its idle-wait + submit-retry helpers (sable_pane_lib) here: --interrupt sends
Escape ONCE then waits for the pane to go IDLE (empty composer prompt AND no
turn still running) before typing — waiting only for the prompt to reappear
raced the interrupted turn's redraw and dropped the message (SABLE-m6is);
submission is retried until the framed message is visible in the pane and no
longer sitting in the input box. Only then do we print `delivered`; on
genuine failure we print `undelivered`, AUTO-FILE the durable for-<role>
inbox bead (SABLE-1umr — delivery degrades to the bead substrate, not to
nothing; set SABLE_MSG_AUTO_FALLBACK=0 to disable, and bead-addressed worker
sends never auto-file since the dispatching manager sees the failure live),
and exit non-zero. If bd itself is unavailable we fall back to printing the
manual bead-filing hint.

Usage:
  sable-msg <to-role> "<text>" [--from <role>] [--interrupt] [--bead]
  sable-msg <to-role> --body-file <path> [--from <role>] [--interrupt] [--bead]
  sable-msg --file-sighting "<text>" [--from <role>]
    --file-sighting file a bead recording an observation (SABLE-441vl) —
                    capture is mandatory, never refused or deferred; priority
                    is a seat estimate a hook later marks provisional. No
                    <to-role>, no tmux, no pane lookup. See
                    file_sighting_bead's docstring below.
    <text>          message body, given inline as the second positional arg.
                    HAZARD (SABLE-tmbx1): the CALLING shell parses this
                    argument before sable-msg ever sees it. A body composed
                    inside a double-quoted (or unquoted) shell argument has
                    its backticks and $(...) COMMAND-SUBSTITUTED by that
                    shell — the substituted command actually RUNS with the
                    caller's privileges, and the delivered message silently
                    loses that text, with sable-msg reporting success. This
                    is not a bug sable-msg can detect: by the time argv
                    reaches main(), the damage is already done. Prefer
                    --body-file for any body that might contain a code
                    reference, shell snippet, or literal backtick/$( — which
                    is the ordinary shape of a code review or incident report.
    --body-file <path>   read the body from a file instead (or from stdin
                    when <path> is '-', matching bd's own --body-file
                    convention). A file's bytes are never parsed by a shell,
                    so backticks/$()/quotes round-trip as literal characters
                    regardless of content. Write the body with the Write tool
                    (or any non-shell means) first, then pass only the path
                    on the command line — the path is the only thing the
                    calling shell ever sees, and it need not be prose.
                    Mutually exclusive with the inline <text> positional.
    --from <role>   sender label for the framing header. Default: on a WORKER
                    pane (SABLE_WORKER_PANE=1) this is ALWAYS 'worker:<bead>'
                    (or plain 'worker' if the bead can't be resolved) — NEVER
                    $CLAUDE_AGENT_NAME, which on a worker pane is stamped with
                    the owning LANE MANAGER's name for push-attribution
                    (SABLE-bldh.13), not the worker's own identity (SABLE-qqcd:
                    a worker's self-report must not be framed as its manager's
                    directive). Elsewhere: $CLAUDE_AGENT_NAME, or "operator".
    --interrupt     send Escape first so the message lands NOW instead of queueing
                    behind the recipient's current turn
    --bead          resolve <to-role> as a bead id against a WORKER pane's
                    @sable_bead tag (SABLE-6izz) instead of a manager @sable_role

Env:
  SABLE_TMUX_SOCKET      tmux socket name (-L); for session isolation / tests
  CLAUDE_AGENT_NAME      default --from value (non-worker panes only; see above)
  SABLE_WORKER_PANE      when set, forces the default --from to 'worker:<bead>'
                         (SABLE-qqcd), reusing the SABLE-38zi identity marker
  SABLE_BEAD             bead id for the worker default-from label; falls back
                         to the sending pane's own @sable_bead tag ($TMUX_PANE)
  SABLE_MSG_READY_TIMEOUT   seconds to wait for --interrupt's post-Escape IDLE
                            state — empty prompt AND no running turn (default 25)
  SABLE_MSG_SUBMIT_TRIES    submit-retry attempts (default 8)
  SABLE_MSG_POLL_INTERVAL   seconds between retry polls (default 1.0)

Sender-framing protocol: every message is prefixed with a fixed header line
  ⟦SABLE-MSG⟧ from=<from> to=<to> :: <body>
so the recipient is 100% sure who is speaking. Role files instruct: any turn
starting with ⟦SABLE-MSG⟧ from=<x> is from agent <x>; everything else is the
operator. (Local disambiguator, not a security boundary.)
"""
from __future__ import annotations

import argparse
import os
import re
import subprocess
import sys

# Shared pane-readiness/dispatch helpers (SABLE-bldh.14), same module
# sable-spawn-worker uses. Resolve next to THIS script even via a PATH symlink.
sys.path.insert(0, os.path.dirname(os.path.realpath(__file__)))
from sable_pane_lib import (  # noqa: E402
    SessionCollision, deliver_text, pane_bead_tag, pane_busy, pane_idle,
    pane_process_identity, pane_ready, resolve_session, submitted_own_turn,
    wait_for_idle,
)
from sable_pane_lib import capture_pane as _capture_pane  # noqa: E402

# pane_ready / pane_busy / pane_idle / submitted_own_turn are re-exported (not
# called here directly — wait_for_idle uses pane_idle internally, deliver_text
# uses submitted_own_turn) so the unit suite can assert the predicates via the
# sable_msg module, mirroring sable-spawn-worker's re-export of the pane helpers.
# Do not strip them as "unused" (SABLE-m6is / SABLE-h0jw).

HEADER = "⟦SABLE-MSG⟧"

DEFAULT_READY_TIMEOUT = 25.0
DEFAULT_SUBMIT_TRIES = 8
DEFAULT_POLL_INTERVAL = 1.0


def format_message(frm: str, to: str, body: str) -> str:
    """Single-line framed message. Newlines/runs collapse to single spaces so the
    whole thing is one submitted turn (Enter submits; we never want a mid-body
    newline to submit early)."""
    collapsed = " ".join(body.split())
    return f"{HEADER} from={frm} to={to} :: {collapsed}"


def tmux_base(socket: str | None) -> list[str]:
    return ["tmux", "-L", socket] if socket else ["tmux"]


def resolve_from(socket: str | None = None, run=None) -> str:
    """Default sender label when --from is not given (SABLE-qqcd).

    A worker pane (SABLE_WORKER_PANE=1, stamped ALWAYS by
    sable-spawn-worker:697) is labeled 'worker:<bead>' — or plain 'worker' if
    the bead can't be resolved — regardless of CLAUDE_AGENT_NAME. That env var
    is deliberately stamped with the owning LANE MANAGER's name on a worker
    pane (sable-spawn-worker:696, SABLE-bldh.13: the worker's push must fire
    the manager-gated for-chuck handoff attributed to the lane). Defaulting
    --from to it would make a worker's own status report indistinguishable
    from a real directive from that manager — exactly the trust-boundary bleed
    SABLE-qqcd reported. The bead id comes from $SABLE_BEAD, else the sending
    pane's own @sable_bead tag (its $TMUX_PANE, the tag sable-spawn-worker's
    worker_pane_tags stamps on every worker pane).

    Non-worker panes (managers, the operator) are unaffected: they keep
    $CLAUDE_AGENT_NAME, or "operator" if unset."""
    if os.environ.get("SABLE_WORKER_PANE"):
        bead = os.environ.get("SABLE_BEAD") or pane_bead_tag(
            tmux_base(socket), os.environ.get("TMUX_PANE", ""), run=run)
        return f"worker:{bead}" if bead else "worker"
    return os.environ.get("CLAUDE_AGENT_NAME") or "operator"


def parse_panes(output: str) -> dict[str, str]:
    """Parse `tmux list-panes -F '#{pane_id} #{@sable_role}'` output into
    role -> pane_id. Panes without a role emit just the id (skipped). First
    occurrence of a role wins."""
    mapping: dict[str, str] = {}
    for line in output.splitlines():
        parts = line.split(None, 1)
        if len(parts) < 2:
            continue
        pane_id, role = parts[0], parts[1].strip()
        if role:
            mapping.setdefault(role, pane_id)
    return mapping


def parse_worker_bead_tags(output: str) -> dict[str, list[tuple[str, str]]]:
    """Parse `tmux list-panes -F '#{pane_id} #{@sable_role} #{@sable_bead}
    #{@sable_status}'` output into bead -> [(pane_id, status), ...], restricted
    to panes tagged @sable_role=worker (SABLE-6izz). A manager pane's
    @sable_bead field is never consulted here — bead-addressed lookup is a
    WORKER-only namespace, so a manager-name lookup (parse_panes, above) can
    never collide with it even if some tag is stale. ALL panes sharing a bead
    tag are kept, not last-wins: a REVISE re-spawn into the same worktree
    creates a fresh pane before the old one is reaped, so a done-but-unreaped
    pane and a running pane can legitimately carry the same @sable_bead
    (SABLE-qq6r) — status-aware selection happens in lookup_worker_by_bead."""
    mapping: dict[str, list[tuple[str, str]]] = {}
    for line in output.splitlines():
        parts = line.split(None, 3)
        if len(parts) < 3:
            continue
        pane_id, role, bead = parts[0], parts[1].strip(), parts[2].strip()
        status = parts[3].strip() if len(parts) > 3 else ""
        if role == "worker" and bead:
            mapping.setdefault(bead, []).append((pane_id, status))
    return mapping


def _pane_id_num(pane_id: str) -> int:
    """tmux pane ids (%N) are assigned monotonically increasing server-wide,
    so the numerically largest id among candidates is the newest pane."""
    try:
        return int(pane_id.lstrip("%"))
    except ValueError:
        return -1


class OnlyDonePane(Exception):
    """Raised by lookup_worker_by_bead when every pane tagged with the bead is
    done-but-unreaped (SABLE-qq6r). A REVISE re-spawn into the same worktree
    creates a fresh pane before the old one is reaped, so two panes can share
    one @sable_bead tag; resolving to the done one silently delivers into a
    dead composer while reporting success — a false delivery confirmation,
    worse than an outright failure."""

    def __init__(self, bead_id: str, pane_id: str):
        self.bead_id = bead_id
        self.pane_id = pane_id
        super().__init__(f"bead {bead_id!r} only matches done pane {pane_id}")


def _default_runner(args: list[str]) -> str:
    return subprocess.run(args, capture_output=True, text=True, check=True).stdout


def _scope_args(session: str | None) -> list[str]:
    """Session-scoped listing when a session is known (SABLE-e1e3.3: another
    repo's fleet on the same server must never be enumerated); server-wide -a
    only in the legacy no-session path (tests / direct calls)."""
    return ["-s", "-t", session] if session else ["-a"]


def lookup_pane(role: str, run=None, socket: str | None = None,
                session: str | None = None) -> str | None:
    run = run or _default_runner
    try:
        out = run(tmux_base(socket) + ["list-panes", *_scope_args(session),
                                       "-F", "#{pane_id} #{@sable_role}"])
    except subprocess.CalledProcessError:
        return None  # session not up
    return parse_panes(out).get(role)


def lookup_worker_by_bead(bead_id: str, run=None, socket: str | None = None,
                          session: str | None = None) -> str | None:
    """Resolve a bead id to its live worker pane (SABLE-qq6r). When a REVISE
    re-spawn leaves a done-but-unreaped pane and a fresh running pane sharing
    one @sable_bead tag, prefer the non-done pane (newest by pane id if more
    than one is somehow live); if every matching pane is done, raise
    OnlyDonePane instead of silently resolving to a dead composer."""
    run = run or _default_runner
    try:
        out = run(tmux_base(socket) + [
            "list-panes", *_scope_args(session),
            "-F", "#{pane_id} #{@sable_role} #{@sable_bead} #{@sable_status}",
        ])
    except subprocess.CalledProcessError:
        return None  # session not up
    candidates = parse_worker_bead_tags(out).get(bead_id)
    if not candidates:
        return None
    live = [pane for pane, status in candidates if status != "done"]
    if live:
        return max(live, key=_pane_id_num)
    raise OnlyDonePane(bead_id, max((p for p, _ in candidates), key=_pane_id_num))


def recipient_identity(pane: str, socket: str | None = None) -> str | None:
    """The authoritative process identity of a role-resolved recipient pane, or
    None (SABLE-to8m). Isolated in one function so the role-lookup cross-check in
    main() is a single call and unit tests can stub it hermetically."""
    return pane_process_identity(tmux_base(socket), pane)


def deliver_message(pane: str, message: str, interrupt: bool, socket: str | None = None,
                    run=None, capture=None, sleep=None,
                    ready_timeout: float = DEFAULT_READY_TIMEOUT,
                    tries: int = DEFAULT_SUBMIT_TRIES,
                    interval: float = DEFAULT_POLL_INTERVAL) -> bool:
    """Deliver `message` to `pane`, VERIFIED (SABLE-bq93). --interrupt sends
    Escape ONCE then waits for the pane to go IDLE — an empty composer prompt
    AND no turn still running (wait_for_idle) — before reusing the default-mode
    delivery path (deliver_text). Waiting only for pane_ready was the SABLE-m6is
    bug: a busy pane shows the empty composer prompt too, so the interrupt path
    typed WHILE the interrupted turn was still redrawing / clearing the composer
    (spinner redraw, in-flight tool output), and the message was swallowed — two
    consecutive live sends failed all 8 submit attempts. Deferring injection
    until the turn actually settles matches the manual workaround that always
    landed first try (send Escape, let the pane fall idle, then a default-mode
    send). Submission is then retried (deliver_text) until `message` is visible
    in the pane and no longer sitting in the input box. The Escape is sent once
    and the submit-retry counter is unchanged. Returns False (never raises) on
    genuine non-delivery."""
    base = tmux_base(socket)
    run = run or (lambda cmd: subprocess.run(cmd, capture_output=True, text=True).returncode == 0)
    capture = capture or (lambda: _capture_pane(base, pane))

    if interrupt:
        run(base + ["send-keys", "-t", pane, "Escape"])
        if ready_timeout > 0:
            wait_for_idle(base, pane, ready_timeout, interval=interval,
                          capture=capture, sleep=sleep, run=run)

    return deliver_text(base, pane, message, message, tries=tries, interval=interval,
                        run=run, capture=capture, sleep=sleep)


FALLBACK_TITLE_PREFIX = "SABLE-MSG undelivered to"


def fallback_bead_title(to_role: str, message: str) -> str:
    """The title file_fallback_bead gives a durable inbox bead.

    Extracted so callers that need to RECOGNISE such a bead derive the title
    the same way we compose it, instead of hand-typing the format (SABLE-3mrv3).
    Note what `message` is at every real call site: the FRAMED message from
    format_message ('⟦SABLE-MSG⟧ from=<frm> to=<to> :: <body>'), never the raw
    body — so the framing sits between the role and the body, and a title
    guessed as '<prefix> <role>: <body>' matches nothing. That mistake made a
    live-DB-pollution assertion silently unfalsifiable; hence this seam."""
    return f"{FALLBACK_TITLE_PREFIX} {to_role}: {message[:80]}"


def fallback_bead_labels(to_role: str) -> str:
    """The --labels value for a durable inbox bead. Same rationale as
    fallback_bead_title: recognisers must reuse it, not restate it."""
    return f"for-{to_role},coord"


def file_fallback_bead(frm: str, to_role: str, message: str, runner=None) -> str | None:
    """File the durable for-<role> inbox bead when live delivery could not be
    verified (SABLE-1umr). Returns the new bead id, or None when bd is
    unavailable/errored (the caller then prints the manual hint instead).
    Runs in the sender's cwd, which for manager/lead panes is the repo whose
    beads db owns the coordination inbox.

    Filed at P3, NOT P1 (costing-comparison-573). These are INBOX items, not
    work items: at P1 they sorted above genuine P1 engineering beads in
    `bd ready`, and one measured pool held 26 items of which 11 were these —
    roughly doubling the apparent queue and pushing the real work down it. The
    recipient still finds them by the for-<role> label, which is how the inbox
    is read anyway. Do NOT stop filing them: the fallback is what makes an
    unverified delivery lossless, and it has worked correctly every time."""
    runner = runner or (lambda args: subprocess.run(args, capture_output=True, text=True))
    title = fallback_bead_title(to_role, message)
    desc = (f"Auto-filed by sable-msg after verified-delivery failure (SABLE-1umr). "
            f"Deliver this message to {to_role} and act on it: {message} "
            f"[no-test] coordination inbox bead, no code change.")
    try:
        r = runner(["bd", "create", f"--title={title}", f"--description={desc}",
                    "--type=task", "--priority=3",
                    f"--labels={fallback_bead_labels(to_role)}"])
    except Exception:
        return None
    if getattr(r, "returncode", 1) != 0:
        return None
    out = (getattr(r, "stdout", "") or "") + (getattr(r, "stderr", "") or "")
    m = re.search(r"Created issue:\s*(\S+)", out) or re.search(r"([A-Za-z0-9_-]+-[a-z0-9.]+)", out)
    return m.group(1) if m else None


# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Seat sightings (SABLE-441vl) — recording an observation, mandatory capture
# --------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# CAPTURE IS MANDATORY, PRIORITY IS ADVISORY (cockpit ruling, 2026-07-22
# 16:23, recorded as a COMMENT on SABLE-441vl). The bead this implements was
# originally scoped on the premise that the merge seat (chuck) CANNOT create
# work-creating beads at all — that premise is MEASURED FALSE (chuck filed
# seven beads the same day) and the ruling re-scoped the deliverable: the
# seat MUST be free to file what it notices (an unfiled finding is invisible
# by construction), and what it does NOT do is set precedence — priority on
# a seat-filed bead is a SEAT ESTIMATE pending cockpit/manager triage.
#
# `--file-sighting` is therefore a PLAIN `bd create` with no refusal, no
# deferred status, and no promotion step — capture must never be blocked.
# hooks/multi-manager/seat-sighting-gate.sh (a PostToolUse hook that never
# denies) mechanizes the "priority is advisory" half by auto-labeling the
# result `seat-filed` and marking `priority_provisional` afterward, for ANY
# `bd create` under chuck's identity — whether it came through this
# convenience wrapper or a hand-typed `bd create`.

SIGHTING_TITLE_PREFIX = "SEAT-FILED"


def sighting_bead_title(text: str) -> str:
    """The title file_sighting_bead gives a filed bead. Extracted for the
    same reason fallback_bead_title is: a recogniser must derive the title
    the same way we compose it, not hand-type the format."""
    return f"{SIGHTING_TITLE_PREFIX}: {text[:80]}"


def file_sighting_bead(frm: str, text: str, runner=None) -> str | None:
    """File a bead recording an observation the seat noticed (SABLE-441vl).
    A single, ordinary `bd create` — capture is mandatory, so this never
    refuses, defers, or requires a later promotion. Priority is left at bd's
    own default (a seat ESTIMATE, per the ruling); the seat-sighting-gate
    hook marks it provisional afterward, mechanically, regardless of how the
    bead was created. Returns the new bead id, or None when bd is
    unavailable/errored (mirrors file_fallback_bead's contract)."""
    runner = runner or (lambda args: subprocess.run(args, capture_output=True, text=True))
    title = sighting_bead_title(text)
    desc = (f"Filed via `sable-msg --file-sighting` by {frm} (SABLE-441vl: capture is "
            f"mandatory, priority is a seat estimate pending triage): {text}")
    try:
        r = runner(["bd", "create", f"--title={title}", f"--description={desc}", "--type=task"])
    except Exception:
        return None
    if getattr(r, "returncode", 1) != 0:
        return None
    out = (getattr(r, "stdout", "") or "") + (getattr(r, "stderr", "") or "")
    m = re.search(r"Created issue:\s*(\S+)", out) or re.search(r"([A-Za-z0-9_-]+-[a-z0-9.]+)", out)
    return m.group(1) if m else None


def parse_args(argv: list[str]) -> argparse.Namespace:
    p = argparse.ArgumentParser(
        prog="sable-msg",
        description="Message a SABLE agent pane over tmux (lead<->manager, or a bead-addressed worker).",
    )
    p.add_argument("to_role", nargs="?", default=None,
                   help="recipient role (e.g. optimus, tarzan, lincoln), or a bead id "
                        "when --bead is passed. Omit entirely with --file-sighting — a "
                        "sighting contacts no pane and addresses no role.")
    p.add_argument("body", nargs="?", default=None,
                   help="message text (collapsed to a single line). Mutually "
                        "exclusive with --body-file; exactly one is required. "
                        "HAZARD (SABLE-tmbx1): this argument is parsed by the "
                        "CALLING shell before sable-msg sees it — a body "
                        "containing backticks or $(...) gets command-"
                        "substituted (and the substituted command actually "
                        "runs) rather than delivered. Prefer --body-file.")
    p.add_argument("--body-file", dest="body_file", default=None, metavar="PATH",
                   help="read the body from PATH instead of the inline <body> "
                        "argument ('-' reads stdin, matching bd's own "
                        "--body-file convention). A file's content is never "
                        "parsed by a shell, so backticks/$()/quotes round-trip "
                        "literally (SABLE-tmbx1). Mutually exclusive with "
                        "the inline <body> positional.")
    p.add_argument("--from", dest="frm", default=None,
                   help="sender label for the framing header (default: "
                        "'worker:<bead>' on a worker pane, else "
                        "$CLAUDE_AGENT_NAME or \"operator\"; see resolve_from)")
    p.add_argument("--interrupt", action="store_true",
                   help="send Escape first so the message lands immediately")
    p.add_argument("--bead", action="store_true",
                   help="resolve <to_role> as a bead id against a WORKER pane's "
                        "@sable_bead tag instead of a manager @sable_role "
                        "(SABLE-6izz: workers share the generic role 'worker')")
    p.add_argument("--file-sighting", dest="file_sighting", action="store_true",
                   help="file a bead recording an observation instead of messaging a pane "
                        "(SABLE-441vl: capture is mandatory, priority is advisory) — the "
                        "observation comes from the inline <body> or --body-file. No pane "
                        "is contacted and no <to_role> is needed; a plain bd create, never "
                        "refused or deferred. hooks/multi-manager/seat-sighting-gate.sh "
                        "auto-labels the result seat-filed and marks its priority "
                        "provisional afterward, for the merge seat's identity specifically.")
    ns = p.parse_args(argv)
    if ns.file_sighting and ns.to_role is not None and ns.body is None:
        # --file-sighting takes no to_role, so a single positional is the
        # BODY, not a role — argparse fills the first optional positional
        # (to_role) greedily and has no way to know that in advance.
        ns.body, ns.to_role = ns.to_role, None
    if ns.body is not None and ns.body_file is not None:
        p.error("argument body: not allowed with argument --body-file")
    if ns.body is None and ns.body_file is None:
        p.error("one of the arguments body --body-file is required")
    if not ns.file_sighting and not ns.to_role:
        p.error("the following arguments are required: to_role")
    return ns


def resolve_body(ns: argparse.Namespace, stdin=None) -> str:
    """Materialize the message body text from either the inline positional or
    --body-file (SABLE-tmbx1). A file/stdin read never invokes a shell, so
    content read this way cannot be command-substituted no matter what
    metacharacters it contains — unlike the inline positional, which the
    CALLING shell has already parsed by the time argv reaches us."""
    if ns.body_file is None:
        return ns.body
    stdin = stdin or sys.stdin
    if ns.body_file == "-":
        return stdin.read()
    with open(ns.body_file, "r", encoding="utf-8") as fh:
        return fh.read()


def main(argv: list[str] | None = None) -> int:
    ns = parse_args(sys.argv[1:] if argv is None else argv)
    socket = os.environ.get("SABLE_TMUX_SOCKET") or None
    if ns.frm is None:
        ns.frm = resolve_from(socket)

    if ns.file_sighting:
        # No pane, no tmux session, no framing header — a sighting is a bd
        # write, not a message (SABLE-441vl). Resolved and returned BEFORE any
        # session/pane lookup below, which a sighting never needs.
        bead_id = file_sighting_bead(ns.frm, resolve_body(ns))
        if bead_id:
            sys.stderr.write(
                f"sable-msg: filed {bead_id} — capture is mandatory, this bead is live in "
                f"bd ready now; priority is an estimate pending triage.\n")
            return 0
        sys.stderr.write(
            "sable-msg: could not file bead — bd unavailable or errored. "
            "Fall back to: bd create --title=\"SEAT-FILED: ...\" --type=task\n")
        return 1

    try:
        session = resolve_session(socket=socket)
    except SessionCollision as e:
        sys.stderr.write(f"sable-msg: {e}\n")
        return 4

    if ns.bead:
        try:
            pane = lookup_worker_by_bead(ns.to_role, socket=socket, session=session)
        except OnlyDonePane as e:
            sys.stderr.write(
                f"sable-msg: worker pane for bead '{e.bead_id}' is done "
                f"({e.pane_id}), awaiting reap — not a live worker to deliver "
                f"into. Reap it (sable-worker-status --reap) once the fresh "
                f"pane is the only match, then retry.\n"
            )
            return 1
        if pane is None:
            sys.stderr.write(
                f"sable-msg: no worker pane registered for bead '{ns.to_role}' "
                f"in session '{session}' (no @sable_role=worker pane has "
                f"@sable_bead={ns.to_role}). "
                f"Is the worker still running (sable-worker-status)?\n"
            )
            return 1
    else:
        pane = lookup_pane(ns.to_role, socket=socket, session=session)
        if pane is None:
            sys.stderr.write(
                f"sable-msg: no pane registered for role '{ns.to_role}' "
                f"in session '{session}' (no pane there has @sable_role={ns.to_role}). "
                f"Is this repo's SABLE session up (sable-launch)? To address a worker, "
                f"pass --bead <bead-id>.\n"
            )
            return 1
        # SABLE-to8m: the @sable_role tag that resolved this pane is mutable
        # global state a stale/poisoned tag can forge (the 2026-07-07 incident:
        # a corrupt lincoln tag on a worker pane sank two manager escalations
        # into it). Cross-check the RECIPIENT's AUTHORITATIVE process identity
        # (CLAUDE_AGENT_NAME) before delivering: when it disagrees with the
        # requested role the tag is poisoned, so refuse rather than route the
        # traffic into the wrong pane. Unresolvable identity (a pane SABLE did
        # not spawn) fails open — delivery is unchanged for it.
        actual = recipient_identity(pane, socket)
        if actual is not None and actual != ns.to_role:
            sys.stderr.write(
                f"sable-msg: refusing to deliver to role '{ns.to_role}' ({pane}): "
                f"its @sable_role tag is poisoned — the pane's live process "
                f"identity is '{actual}', not '{ns.to_role}' (SABLE-to8m). If this "
                f"pane was moved/resumed, re-register it from inside with "
                f"'sable-relink {ns.to_role}'.\n"
            )
            return 1

    message = format_message(ns.frm, ns.to_role, resolve_body(ns))
    ready_timeout = float(os.environ.get("SABLE_MSG_READY_TIMEOUT", DEFAULT_READY_TIMEOUT))
    submit_tries = int(os.environ.get("SABLE_MSG_SUBMIT_TRIES", DEFAULT_SUBMIT_TRIES))
    poll_interval = float(os.environ.get("SABLE_MSG_POLL_INTERVAL", DEFAULT_POLL_INTERVAL))
    landed = deliver_message(pane, message, ns.interrupt, socket=socket,
                             ready_timeout=ready_timeout, tries=submit_tries,
                             interval=poll_interval)
    if not landed:
        bead_id = None
        if not ns.bead and os.environ.get("SABLE_MSG_AUTO_FALLBACK", "1") != "0":
            bead_id = file_fallback_bead(ns.frm, ns.to_role, message)
        if bead_id:
            sys.stderr.write(
                f"sable-msg: undelivered {ns.frm} -> {ns.to_role} ({pane}); the message did not "
                f"land as a submitted turn after {submit_tries} attempt(s). Filed durable inbox "
                f"bead {bead_id} (label for-{ns.to_role}) so it survives.\n"
            )
        else:
            sys.stderr.write(
                f"sable-msg: undelivered {ns.frm} -> {ns.to_role} ({pane}); the message did not "
                f"land as a submitted turn after {submit_tries} attempt(s). Fall back to a durable "
                f"inbox bead: bd create --title=\"<summary>\" --label=for-{ns.to_role} --type=task\n"
            )
        return 1

    sys.stderr.write(f"sable-msg: delivered {ns.frm} -> {ns.to_role} ({pane})\n")
    return 0


if __name__ == "__main__":
    sys.exit(main())
